THIS SHIPMENT SPILLED IN THE FEDEX WAREHOUSE DURING THE SORT.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE CONTENTS THE ITEM THAT LEAKED APPEARED TO BE CHLOROFORM.  THERE WERE SEVERAL OTHER CHEMICALS IN THE PACKAGE.  MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEETS OBTAINED ON THE CONTENTS ARE ENCLOSED.  THIS SHIPMENT HAD NO DANGEROUS GOODS PACKAGE MARKINGS, LABELING, OR DOCUMENTATION.  OF THE ITEMS IN THE PACKAGE, IT IS BELIEVED THAT FIVE OF THE CHEMICALS ARE UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS (1) ONE IS BELIEVED TO BE CHLOROFORM, HAZARD CLASS 6.1, UN1888 WHICH SPILLED.  MSDS ENCLOSED IN THIS.  (2) PRODUCT NAME ZINC REAGENT POWDER LISTS A ORAL RAT 200 MG/KG.  THIS IS BELIEVED TO BE A 6.1 PACKING GROUP III, TOXIC SOLID, INORGANIC NOS. MSDS ENCLOSED. (3) PRODUCT NAME ZINC CONDITIONING REAGENT. THIS LISTS AN ORAL TOXICITY NUMBER OF 200MG/KG ALSO.  THIS BELIEVED TO BE A 6.1 PACKING GROUP III, TOXIC SOLID, INORGANIC NOS MSDS ENCLOSED (4) PRODUCT NAME BUFFER SOLUTION, SEE MSDS ENCLOSED.  THIS HAS A PROPER SHIPPING NAME OF HYDROCHLORIC ACID SOLUTION, HAZARD CLASS 8, UN1789, PACKING GROUP III ON IT.  THAT IS WHAT IS  BELIEVED TO BE (5)  THE 5TH ITEM BELIEVED TO BE UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS HAS A PROPER SHIPPING NAME OF METHANOL SOLUTION, UN1230, HAZARD CLASS 3, PACKING GROUP II ON IT.  FOLLOWING PROPER SPILL CLEANUP PROCEDURES THIS PACKAGE WAS CONTAINED IN SALVAGE DRUM.  FAA AGENT MIKE GIVENS WAS NOTIFIED.  FEDEX WILL HOLD THE SHIPMENT PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION.

IT IS UNKNOWN WHETHER THE INNER GLASS AMPOULE HAD BEEN BROKEN.  IF IT HAD, THE GLASS AMPOULE ORIGINALLY CONTAINED 5ML OF INFECTIOUS SUBSTANCES. PROPER SPILL CLEANUP PROCEDURES OCCURRED AND THE PACKAGE WAS CONTAINED IN THE SALVAGE DRUM PENDING DISPOSITION.  I NOTIFIED LYNN MEYERS AT THE CENTER FOR DISEASE CONTROL IN CASE ANY OF THE 5ML HAD SPILLED.  ACCORDING TO A PHONE CONVERSATION WITH THE SHIPPER, THE PACKAGE ALSO CONTAINED A NONHAZARDOUS GEL PAK.  IT IS POSSIBLE THAT SPILLED MATERIAL WAS THE GEL PAK AND NOT THE INFECTIOUS SUBSTANCES ITSELF.  THERE WERE NO PACKAGE DISCREPANCIES NOTED WITH THE SHIPMENT.

DURING AN UNUSUALLY LARGE RAINFALL EVENT, THE BULK SOLID CONTAINER FILLED WITH RAINWATER. THE RAINWATER SEEPED DOWN THROUGH THE DIRT AND LEAKED OUT OF A SMALL HOLE THAT UNKNOWINGLY EXISTED IN THE BOTTOM OF THE BOX. BOWS HAD BEEN LEFT OFF THE TOP OF THE BOX, CAUSING MORE RAIN TO ENTER THE BOX THAN WOULD HAVE OCCURRED IF THE BOWS HAD BEEN IN PLACE. APPROXIMATELY 15 GALLONS WERE RELEASED TO THE SOIL ADJACENT TO THE PAD AT THE TRANSFER FACILITY. THERE WERE 3 CUBIC YARDS OF SOIL REMOVED FROM THE AREA. THE MATERIAL WAS PROMPTLY CONTAINERIZED AND SENT TO LWD, INC FOR INCINERATION. THE BOX HAS BEEN TAKEN OUT OF SERVICE TO REPAIR THE SMALL HOLE. EMPLOYEES HAVE BEEN REMINDED OF THE IMPORTANCE OF PLACING BOWS ON THE ROLL-OFF BOXES.

column168: AFTER THE DRIVER RECEIVED THE OKAY TO UNLOAD, HE STARTED TRANSFER FROM CARGO TANK VIA PUMP ON TRACTOR INTO CONSIGNEE'S STORAGE TANK.  WHEN GAUGE ON STORAGE TANK SHOWED 92%,  A WARNING LIGHT CAME ON AND DRIVER SHUT OFF PUMP AND NOTIFIED UNLOADER.  DRIVER CHECKED AMOUNT IN CARGO TANK AND RELAYED INFORMATION TO UNLOADER. HE TOLD DRIVER TO START UP PUMP -  STORAGE TANK WOULD HOLD BALANCE OF PRODUCT AND HE WOULD WATCH STORAGE TANK.  JUST AS THE CARGO TANK WENT EMPTY, THE AUTOMATIC VALVE CLOSED, CAUSED PRESSURE IN LINE AND BLEW HOSE IN HOSE.  DRIVER AND CONSIGNEE CLEANED UP AREA.
AT THE END OF OFF-LOADING, THE PRODUCT CAME OUT THE TOP OF THE STORAGE TANK.  THE CONSIGNEE PUT ABSORBANT POWDER ON THE SPILLED PRODUCT, SWEPT IT UP AND PUT IT INTO A DRUM FOR DISPOSAL.

CONSIGNEE UNLOADER WAS DRUMMING WITH NOZZLE INTO TOTES AND DRIVER OF CARGO TANK WAS IN CONTROL OF PUMP ON TRACTOR.  UNLOADER FAILED TO ALERT DRIVER TO SHUT DOWN PUMP WITH NE WAS SHUTTING OFF NOZZLE.  AS A RESULT, DRUMMING NOZZLE BLEW OFF AND PRODUCT SPRAYED ON TRAILER AND TOTES.  CONSIGNEE SPREAD OIL DRY ON SPILLED PRODUCT AND CLEANED UP AREA.

THE TANK CAR WAS FOUND TO HAVE A DEFECTIVE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE WHICH COULD NOT BE CAPPED AND CONTAINED DUE TO EXCESSIVE PRESSURE IN THE TANK CAR.  THE CONSIGNEE DESPATCHED TANK TRUCK OF CAUSTIC SOLUTION  TO THE SITE AND VENTED THE EXCESSIVE TANK CAR PRESSURE THROUGH THE SOLUTION, SCRUBBING ALL VAPORS OF HAZARDOUS CHARACTERISTICS BEFORE VENTING INTO THE ATMOSPHERE.  A;; PM-SITE RESPONSE ACTIONS WERE DIRECTED AND SUPERVISED BY THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS UNITS.  UPON COMPLETION OF VENTING PROCESS, THE DEFECTIVE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE WAS THE N CAPPED WITH A "C" KIT--CONTAINING THE LEAK. THE SHIPPER THEN ATTAINED THE REQUIRED FRA EXEMPTION TO MOVE THE CAR TO THE NEAREST QUALIFIED FACILITY FOR REPAIR.

A STEEL 55- GALLON DRUM CONTAINING RESIN SOLUTION WAS PUNCTURED BY IMPROPER USE OF A FORKLIFT ATTACHMENT BY A NON-REGULAR EMPLOYEE.  THE CASUAL DOCKMAN/DRIVER WAS ATTEMPTING TO CLAMP A DRUM UNLOADER ATTACHMENT TO TWO DRUMS LOCATED SIDE BY SIDE AGAINST THE FAR RIGHT SIDE WALL IN THE NOSE OF A ROAD DUB TRAILER. THE FAILURE OCCURRED WHEN THE DOCKMAN FORCED THE OUTSIDE CLAMP BLADE AGAINST THE TRAILER WALL WHICH DIRECTED THE END OF THE CURVED CLAMP BLADE INTO THE SIDE OF THE DRUM, SPILLING IT'S CONTENTS.  THE DOCKMAN REPORTED THE SPILL AS A "LEAK" AND IMMEDIATE ACTION WAS TAKEN TO CONTAIN THE EXTENT OF THE SPILL.  THE FAILURE WAS DISCUSSED WITH THE DOCKMAN AND A REPRIMAND IN THE FORM OF A SUSPENSION WAS LEVIED.  UPON CONTACTING THE MANUFACTURER AND THE CONSIGNEE, A SPILL CONTAINMENT AND CLEAN UP CREW WAS CONTACTED AND DEPLOYED TO COMPLETE THE CLEAN UP PROCESS, AND PACKAGE THE CONTAMINATED MATERIAL INTO CONTAINERS SUITABLE FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.

THE AREA WAS IMMEDIATELY CORDONED OFF AND CHEMTREC AND SHIPPER WERE CALLED FOR ASSISTANCE. SAFETY SUPERVISOR WAS ALSO CONTACTED.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT CONSOLIDATED FREIGHTWAYS WAS NOT PROPERLY EQUIPPED TO CLEAN UP SPILL AND BAY WEST WAS CALLED IN FOR PROFESSIONAL CLEAN-UP.  SHORTLY AFTER SPILL AREA WAS CORDONED OFF, ANOTHER FREIGHT HANDLER BEGAN EXPERIENCING ITCHY, BLOTCHINESS AND BURNING OF HIS EYES.  HE HAD BEEN WORKING APPROXIMATELY 80 FEET FROM SPILL AREA.  HE WAS SENT TO HOSPITAL FOR ATTENTION WHERE IT WAS DISCOVERED HE HAD EXPERIENCED AN ALLERGIC REACTION TO THE FORMALDEHYDE. HE WAS TREATED AND RELEASED.

EMPLOYEE WAS UNLOADING DRUMS FROM VEHICLE MANUALLY ROLLED DRUM FROM TRUCK TO DOCK PLATE AND WAS ATTEMPTING TO ROLL ONTO PALLET LOCATED ON WAREHOUSE FLOOR.  DRUM SLID ON DOCK PLATE EMPLOYEE LOST CONTROL AND LET IT DROP TO THE FLOOR, THIS CAUSED THE RING ON THE DRUM TO COME OPEN WHICH IN TURN LOOSENED THE SEAL OF THE LID TO THE DRUM, WHICH ALLOWED A SMALL AMOUNT OF MATERIAL TO LEAK OUT OF THE DRUM. TWO MORE EMPLOYEES HELPED THE INITIAL  EMPLOYEE RIGHT THE DRUM IN A MATTER OF SECONDS, AND IMMEDIATELY BEGAN DIKING W/ BETONITE CLAY ABSORBENT AND CLEANED UP THE SPILLED MATERIAL.  DETERMINED THE LOCKING MECHANISM ON THE DRUM HAD NOT BEEN ENGAGED WHEN DRUM WAS LOADED.  REVIEWED QA/QC PROCEDURES AND DRUM HANDLING PROCEDURES WITH FACILITY EMPLOYEES AT SUBSEQUENT SAFETY MEETING TO HELP PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS, ALSO SUPPLIED STAFF W/MATERIAL NECESSARY TO LOCK RINGS ON THESE TYPES OF DRUMS.

column14: US HWY 53 N. AT MINNESOTA HWY
column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: ON 6-22-98, AN EDWARDS OIL TANKER WAS TRANSPORTING #2 FUEL OIL TO INLAND STEEL'S MINORCA MINE IN VIRGINIA, MINNESOTA, ALONG U.S. HIGHWAY 53 NORTH. AT 2:45 AM, AT THE MINNESOTA HIGHWAY 135 EXIT-LOCATED NORTH OF EVELETH, MN AND SOUTH OF VIRGINIA, MN-THE TRANSPORT DRIVER FAILED TO FOLLOW THE HIGHWAY, WHICH CURVED TO THE LEFT AND DROVE ONTO THE MEDIAN BETWEEN HWY 53 NORTH AND THE HWY 135 EXIT RAMP. HE HIT THE EXIT SIGN LOCATED ON THE MEDIAN, THEN SWERVED TO THE RIGHT, OFF OF THE MEDIAN AND ONTO THE EXIT RAMP. HE CONTINUED TO SWERVE TO THE RIGHT ON THE EXIT RAMP UNTIL HE REACHED THE RIGHT SHOULDER OF THE EXIT RAMP. AT THAT POINT, HE TRIED TO TURN TO THE LEFT TO SWERVE BACK ONTO THE PAVEMENT OF THE EXIT RAMP. DUE TO ITS FORWARD MOMENTUM, THE TRUCK AND ITS TANK TRAILER SLID ALONG THE PAVEMENT OF THE EXIT RAMP FOR APPROXIMATELY 80 YARDS BEFORE COMING TO REST ACROSS THE RAMP (SEE ATTACHED DIAGRAM). THE EXACT CAUSE OF THE ACCIDENT IS NOT KNOWN AT THIS TIME. THE DRIVER WAS TAKEN TO THE NEAREST HOSPITAL EMERGENCY ROOM FOR TREATMENT OF A BRUISED NECK AND SHOULDERS AND THEN WAS RELEASED. THERE WERE NO OTHER VEHICLES OR PERSONS INVOLVED IN THIS ACCIDENT. THE SLIDE ALONG THE PAVEMENT RUPTURED ALL OF THE INTERNAL BAFFLES IN THE TANK TRAILER, AS WELL AS GOUGING TWO HOLES IN THE EXTERNAL WALL OF THE TRAILER. THIS CAUSED APPROXIMATELY 5800 GALLONS OF FUEL OIL TO LEAK OUT ONTO THE PAVEMENT AND THEN FLOW INTO THE DRAINAGE DITCH ALONG ONE SIDE OF THE EXIT RAMP. THE SPILLED OIL FLOWED FROM THE ONE DRAINAGE DITCH THROUGH THE CULVERT TO THE OTHER DRAINAGE DITCH AND THEN INTO THE SMALL CREEK THAT DRAINED THE DRAINAGE DITCHES. ALL THE PROPER AUTHORITIES WERE NOTIFIED IMMEDIATLY, INCLUDING THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER, MINNESOTA POLLUTION CONTROL AGENCY, AND THE US AND MINNESOTA DEPARTMENTS OF TRANSPORTATION. A SPILL RESPONSE TEAM CAME TO THE SCENE IMMEDIATELY TO BEGIN CONTAINMENT AND CLEAN UP EFFORTS. THE OIL REMAINING IN THE TRUCK WAS PUMPED FROM THE TRUCK AND TRANSPORTED FROM THE SCENE FOR STORAGE. THE SPILL RESPONSE TEAM COLLECTED AS MUCH OF THE SPILLED OIL FROM THE ACCIDENT SITE AS WAS POSSIBLE. THEN THEY DUG TWO SUMP HOLES, ONE IN EACH OF THE DITCHES. TO HELP COLLECT THE REMAINING OIL SO THAT IT COULD BE PUMPED OUT AND REMOVED OVER THE NEXT FEW WEEKS. DOWNSTREAM, IN THE CREEK THAT DRAINED THE TWO DITCHES, A CONCRETE DAM WAS BUILT TO KEEP THE SPILLED OIL FROM FLOWING ANY FURTHER BEYOND THAT POINT AND TO CREATE A SMALL POND WHERE THE OIL COULD BE SKIMMED FROM THE TOP OF THE WATER.

THIS COMPOUND CONDITION ALLOWED AMMONIA TO SEEP PAST THE TWO INCH VALVE AND ESCAPE TO THE ATMOSPHERE THROUGH THE BLEEDER VALVE. THE PLANT PERSONNEL SECURED THE VALVES AND THE LINE WAS BLOWN CLEAR.  A SMALL RESIDUAL AMOUNT OF AMMONIA WAS ALLOWED TO EVAPORATE TO THE ATMOSPHERE.  THE OPERATOR OF THE TRAILER HAS BEEN RETRAINED IN THE PROPER CLOSURE PROCEDURES THAT ARE IN PLACE TO PREVENT THIS SITUATION FROM OCCURING.

column168: DRIVER HAD TRUCK TRAILER POSITIONED UNDER SHIPPER LOADING RACK AND HAD THE LOADING FUNCTION IN FULL OPERATION.  DRIVER LEFT THE CATWALK AND WENT TO HIS TRAILER CAB FOR SOMETHING.  WHILE THERE, HE DISCOVERED THE TANK TRAILER HAD FILLED, WHICH WAS THE DESIRED VOLUME FOR THIS "LIGHT IN WEIGHT"  WEAK ACID.  HE STATES THAT HE ATTEMPTED TO OPERATE THE EMERGENCY SWITCH ON THE CUSTOMER LOADING SYSTEM AND THAT IT DID NOT STOP THE LOADING OF PRODUCT. THE TRAILER OVERFLOWED, AND PRODUCT RAN DOWN INTO CONTAINMENT AREA.  SHIPPER PERSONNEL SHUT DOWN THE LOADING.  THE EMERGENCY SWITCH WAS TESTED BY THE SHIPPER'S SAFETY MANAGER, AND IT WAS VERIFIED THAT IT WAS OPERATING PROPERLY.  WE ATTRIBUTE THIS SPILLAGE TO HUMAN ERROR ON THE PART OF THE DRIVER.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES, AND NO PRODUCT REACHED ANY WATERWAYS.  SHIPPER PERSONNEL NEUTRALIZED THE PRODUCT AND CLEANED IT UP.

DEFECTIVE RUBBER LINING ALLOWING PRODUCT TO CORRODE SUMP WALL, GATX 12409, JUNE 4, 1998, PHILADELPHIA DIVISION.  AT APPROXIMATELY 1710 HOURS, THURSDAY, JUNE 4, 1998, CONRAIL'S M & W EMPLOYEE REPORTED PASSING CONRAIL TRAIN ALCS-4 WITH LEAKING TANK CAR GATX 12409 CONTAINING FERRIS CHLORIDE, SOLUTION.  APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATION MADE.  THE TRAIN WAS STOPPED AND THE TANK CAR WAS ISOLATED ON #2 STOWE YARD TRACK IN POTTSTOWN, PA. CONRAIL'S HAZARDOUS MATERIAL FIELD SERVICE MANAGER ARRIVED AT THE SITE.  AT APPROXIMATELY 1945 HOURS,  JUNE 4, 1998,  REPRESENTATIVES FROM REACT, A CONTRACT ENVIRONMENTAL REMEDIATION COMPANY ARRIVED AT THE SITE AND UPON EXAMINING THE CAR DETERMINED IT HAD A DEFECTIVE RUBBER LINING ALLOWING PRODUCT TO CORRODE SUMP WALL. REPAIRS WERE MADE BY REACT WHO PLUGGED THE HOLE IN SUMP WITH A WOODEN PLUG THUS SECURING THE LEAK AND CLEANED UP SPILLED AREA.  THE PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED BY VACUUM TRUCK AND RETURNED TO US STEEL IN FAIRLESS, PA.  AN FRA APPROVAL WAS RECEIVED TO TRANSPORT THE TANK CAR BACK TO RESCAR IN DUBOIS FOR INSPECTION AND REPAIR OF THE LINING.

column168: A BULK SHIPMENT OF ANHYDROUS AMMONIA WAS ENROUTE WHEN OUR DRIVER, WHILE MAKING A LANE CHANGE, NOTICED THAT THE CABINET DOOR ON THE CARGO TANK HAD OPENED.  THIS CABINET IS LOCATED BOTTOM-CENTER OF THE TRAILER.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY PULLED OVER.  WHEN PULLING OVER A 1" HOSE APPROXIMATELY 100 FEET LONG PARTIALLY FELL OUT OF THE CABINET AND WAS RUN OVER BY THE TRAILER.  THIS HOSE WAS CHARGED WITH LIQUID ANHYDROUS AMMONIA.  THE AMMONIA IN THE HOSE WAS RELEASED TO THE ATMOSPHERE.  (THE LIQUID AMMONIA WILL VAPORIZE TO A GAS WHEN IT HITS THE ATMOSPHERE).  WHEN THE RELEASE WAS OVER, THE DRIVER APPROACHED THE CABINET AND MADE SURE THAT ALL VALVES WERE SECURE. HE PUT THE HOSE BACK INTO THE CABINET AND SECURED THE CABINET.  THE TRAILER RETURNED TO OUR FACILITY AND WAS REMOVED FROM SERVICE.  THE TRAILER HAS BEEN TO A SHOP TO REPAIR THE CABINET.

column168: SHIPMENT WAS BEING PROCESSED AS AN EXCEPTION WHEN THE DISCREPANCY WAS DISCOVERED.  THE SHIPMENT HAD BEEN REFUSED EARLIER IN THE DAY BECAUSE OF LEAKAGE AND ODOR.  WHEN THE PACKAGE WAS BROUGHT BACK TO THE STATION IT WAS CONTAINED BY A DANGEROUS GOODS AGENT WHO REQUESTED AN MSDS FROM THE SHIPPER.  INFORMATION ON THE MSDS REVEALED THAT THE MATERIAL'S FLASHPOINT WAS SUCH THAT THE COMMODITY SHOULD HAVE BEEN DECLARED AS A FLAMMABLE LIQUID.  THERE WERE NO HAZMAT MARKINGS OR LABELS EXHIBITED ON THE OUTER SURFACE OF THE PACKAGE NOR WAS THERE A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS IN EVIDENCE WITH THE SHIPMENT.  THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION TO THE FAA FOR INVESTIGATION.

THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING PROCESSED DURING THE OUTBOUND SORT WHEN THE DISCREPANCY WAS DISCOVERED.  THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING HANDLED BY HANDLING PERSONNEL WHEN THE UNIT WAS ACCIDENTLY TIPPED OVER.  THIS ALLOWED THE LIQUID NITROGEN TO SPILL OUT OF THE UNIT.  THE SHIPPER WAS ATTEMPTING TO USE THE DRY DEWAR SHIPPING PROVISION WHICH ALLOWS THE USE OF A SPECIALIZED, INSULATED UNIT IN WHICH THE LIQUID NITROGEN IS FULLY ABSORBED IN TO THE WALLS OF THE CYLINDER.  AS LONG AS THERE IS NO FREE STANDING LIQUID NITROGEN IN THE CONTAINER THEN THE UNIT DOES NOT HAVE TO BE SHIPPED ACCORDING TO  THE PROVISIONS OF THE UN/ICAO REGULATIONS AND THE DOMESTIC HMRS (49CFR).  AS THERE WAS FREE STANDING LIQUID NITROGEN EXHIBITED THIS CONSTITUTED A POSSIBLE UNDECLARED DG SHIPMENT.  THERE WERE NO HAZMAT MARKINGS OR LABELS EXHIBITED ON THE OUTER SURFACE OF THE DEWAR NOR WAS THERE A SHIPPER DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS IN EVIDENCE WITH THE SHIPMENT.  THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION TO THE FAA FOR INVESTIGATION.

column168: WHILE SWITCHING RCRX 1297 THE TRAIN CREW OBSERVED LIQUID DRIPPING FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR. THE ANK CAR WAS ISOLATED, AND THE PROPER AUTHORITIES NOTIFIED. EMERGENCY RESPONSE CREWS ATTEMPTED TO CONTAIN THE SPILLAGE USING ABSORBENT PADS. ONCE DEEMED SAFE FOR MOVEMENT THE CAR WAS MOVED TO A LOCATION WHERE REPAIR CREWS COULD REPAIR/REPLACE LEAKING FITTINGS. THE SHIPPER'S RESPONSE TEAM INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND THAT THE BOLTS ON THE BLIND FLANGE FOR THE LIQUID EDUCTION PIPE WERE LOOSE AND CORRODED. THIS LOOSE FLANGE HAD ALLOWED PRODUCT ESCAPE. USING A VAPOR SCRUBBER, THE REPAIR TEAM RELIEVED PRESSURE IN THE CAR AND REMOVED THE BLIND FLANGE. NEW BOLTS AND GASKET WERE INSTALLED ON THE LIQUID EDUCTION FLANGE AND THE CAR WAS REINSPECTED. NO FURTHER DEFECTS WERE FOUND AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT.

column168: Q31619 DERAILED 30 CARS IN A GENERAL PILE UP AT COX LANDING, WV (MP BA107). THE DERAILMENT INCLUDED 10 LOADS OF PETROLEUM COKE, 2 LOADS OF SCRAP IRON, 2 LOADS OF COIL STEEL, 5 EMPTY COVERED HOPPERS  & 11 HAZMAT TANK CARS. THE HAZMATS INCLUDE 8 RESIDUE TANK CARS, 2 LOADS OF FORMALDEHYDE SOL. & 1 LOAD OF MOLTEN SULFUR. THE 2 CARS FORMALDEHYDE WERE RUPTURED & RELEASED APPROX. 22, 000 GALLONS OF PRODUCT. THE FIRE DEPT. EVACUATED ABOUT 500 PEOPLE INITIALLY. THIS WAS REDUCED TO 15  HOUSEHOLD BY 1800 HRS. IT WAS REPORTED THAT 6 PEOPLE (THE CONDUCTOR  5 CIVILIANS) WERE TAKEN TO A LOCAL HOSPITAL WITH IRRITATION SYMPTOMS. THEY WERE TREATED  RELEASED. CLEANUP CONTINUED THROUGH JULY 3RD DURING WHICH 27,550 GALLONS OF FORMALDEHYDE WAS RECOVERED (INCLUDING 16,500 GALS FROM THE DAMAGED TANK CARS). 5,000 CUBIC YARDS OF IMPACTED SOILS WERE EXCAVATED & STAGED PENDING DISPOSAL.

column168: ON JUNE 24, 1998 AT 20:32 CDT, A TRACTOR  SEMI-TRAILER COMBINATION OPERATED BY TRI-STATE MOTOR TRANSIT CO., EXPERIENCED A RIGHT FRONT STEERING TIRE FAILURE, WHILE TRAVELING NORTHBOUND AT THE I-94, I-894 INTERCHANGE NEAR MILWAUKEE, WI.  THE TRAILER WAS LADEN WITH 46,940 POUNDS OF BLASTING AGENTS.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS BEING TRANSPORTED UNDER DOT EXEMPTION NUMBER 8554.  THE DRIVER OF THE VEHICLE, UNABLE TO CONTROL THE DIRECTION OF TRAVEL, STRUCK A GUARD RAIL RUPTURING THE RIGHT DIESEL FUEL TANK. SPARKS FROM THE RIGHT FRONT STEERING WHEEL IGNITED THE DIESEL FUEL CAUSING THE TRACTOR TO BURN.  THE ENSUING FIRE DESTROYED THE TRACTOR.  THE TRAILER MAINTAINED ITS STRUCTURAL INTEGRITY. THE HEAT OF THE FIRE CAUSED MINOR CRYSTALLIZATION OF THE PRODUCT. THE MILWAUKEE FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED.  THE INTERSTATE WAS SHUTDOWN AND APPROXIMATELY 900 CITIZENS WERE EVACUATED WITHIN A 1/2 MILE RADIUS OF THE VEHICLE.  THE FIRE WAS ALLOWED TO BURN OUT.  ANOTHER TRACTOR-TRAILER WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE AND THE PRODUCT WAS PUMPED FROM THE DAMAGED TRAILER INTO THE REPLACEMENT TRAILER. THE ROAD CLOSURE AND EVACUATION LASTED APPROXIMATELY  EIGHTEEN HOURS. RESPONDING AGENCIES INCLUDED THE MILWAUKEE COUNTY SHERIFF DEPARTMENT, MILWAUKEE FIRE DEPARTMENT, MILWAUKEE POLICE DEPARTMENT AND WISCONSIN DEPARTMENT OF NATURAL RESOURCES.  TRI-STATE CONTRACTED WITH SUPERIOR SPECIAL SERVICES, INC., TO PERFORM NECESSARY REMEDIATION WORK AND EMERGENCY RESPONSE.  AT 20:50 CDT, TELEPHONIC NOTIFICATION WAS MADE TO THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER, REPORT NO. 443192.  INITIAL NOTIFICATION TO THE MILWAUKEE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND THE MILWAUKEE COUNTY SHERIFFS DEPARTMENT WAS MADE BY THE DRIVER CALLING 911 ON A CELLULAR TELEPHONE.  AFTER THE PRODUCT WAS TRANSLOADED, IT WAS MOVED BACK TO ORIGIN AT CHARLESTOWN, IN.  THE CAUSE OF THE RIGHT FRONT STEERING TIRE FAILURE HAS NOT BEEN DETERMINED. THE FIRE CONSUMED ALL PHYSICAL EVIDENCE OF THE TIRE.  SEE THE ATTACHED MILWAUKEE COUNTY SHERIFF REPORT AND INCIDENT RESPONSE REPORT COMPLETED BY SUPERIOR SPECIAL SERVICES, INC.

AS THE PACKAGE WAS NOT MARKED OR LABELED AS DANGEROUS GOODS, THEY OPENED IT CONFIRM IF THE CONTENTS WERE DRY ICE OR NOT.  IT APPEARED TO HAVE DRY ICE PELLETS.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS REPORTED TO F.A.A. column168: CALL TO THE BOX LINE FOUND HAZ.  PACKAGE SLIGHTLY WET.  TOOK THE DMP, NEUTRALIZED SMALL AMOUNT OF CHEMICAL AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER THE REST USING UPS SALVAGE TRUCK.

ABX FLYT ARRIVED AT 0546 3 EMPLOYEES WENT INTO THE PLANE TO UNLOAD THE TOPSIDE.  AFTER UNLOADING THE C CONTAINERS FOR ABOUT 10 MILES, THE 3 EMPLOYEES CAME OFF THE PLANE COMPLAINING OF BURNING EYES AND THROATS.  SUSPECTED SOME TYPE OF HAZ SPILL SO WE CONTACTED EXPRESS SUPPORT HAZ DEPT, DIA HAZ AND FIRE DEPARTMENT. DIA HAZ TEAM FOUND THE LEAKING PACKAGE IN A C CONTAINER THAT HAD ALREADY COME OFF THE PLANE.  HAZ TEAM VERIFIED THE CONTENTS AS FORMALDEHYDE.  CALLED THE SKIPPER TO GET AN DISCRITPTION OF WHAT WAS BEING SHIPPED.  HAD WEST HAZ COME OUT AND CLEAN UP SPILL AND PUT SHIPMENT IN A SEALED CONTAINER. 3 EMPLOYEES TAKEN TO HOSPITAL TO TREAT SYMPTOMS OF BURNING THROAT EYES.  ALL WERE RELEASED AT ABOUT 1030.

column168: DRIVER RETURNED TO SERVICE CENTER DUE TO SHIPMENT BEING UNDELIVERABLE DUE TO FORKLIFT BEING DOWN AND NO WAY TO UNLOAD. AT THE TIME DRIVER ARRIVED BACK AT CENTER, HE NOTICED SOME LIQUID ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER. THE SUPERVISOR LOOKED AT THE SHIPMENT AND COULD NOT DETERMINE THAT THE SHIPMENT WAS LEAKING. AT THAT TIME, THE SUPERVISOR SET COULD NOT DETERMINE THAT THE SHIPMENT WAS LEAKING. AT THAT TIME, THE SUPERVISOR SET ON DOCK AT 1500. APPROXIMATELY 3 HRS LATER, THERE WAS A PUDDLE OF APROX. 2-3" IN DIAMETER. AT THAT TIME, SUPERVISOR CALLED NALCO AND ONLY GOT WAS RECORDING SUP THEN CALLED THE EMERGENCY NUMBER ON THE FREIGHT BILL WHICH IS 1-800-462-5378. HE WAS LATER CONTACTED BY DAVE KOBE WITH NALCO. NALCO THEN SENT CET ENVIRONMENTAL TO COME TO SERVICE CENTER AND CORRECT AND CONTAIN HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. TOTE WAS PUMPED INTO 3 .55 GAL POLY DRUMS. ALL SHIPMENT WILL BE RETURNED TO NALCO (SHIPPER ORIGIN) INCLUDING 3 POLY DRUMS.

A STRONG SMELL IN CABIN WAS DETECTED WHILE A /C WAS LOADING.  THE FLIGHT CREW LOCATED THE SOURCE OF THE SMELL.  THE PASSENGER AND CARRY ON WERE REMOVED FROM THE A/C  24 BOTTLES OF FUEL INJECTION CLEANER WERE FOUND IN HIS CARRY ON. APPROXIMATELY 4 FL OZ OF THE PRODUCT HAD SEEPED OUT OF A LOOSE CAP.  ALL SPILLAGE WAS CONTAINED IN THE CARRY ON BAG.  THE CHECKED BAGGAGE WAS ALSO LOCATED AND 77 ADDITIONAL BOTTLES WEE FOUND.  THE ORIGINAL MSDS SENT BY MANUFACTURERS SHOWED MATERIAL TO BE NON-FLAMMABLE PS PER DOT. THE BAGS WERE NOT ALLOWED TO BE PLACED BACK ON A/C AND INFORMATION O N PASSENGER WA OBTAINED.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION 6/11/1998 THE CORRECT MSDS SHOWING PRODUCT TO BE FLAMMABLE WAS LOCATED .  THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED AND A COMPLETE INVESTIGATION OF THE PASSENGER IS BEING EXECUTED.  THE MANUFACTURER IS INVESTIGATING THE POSSIBILITY THAT THE PRODUCT WAS MIS-LABELED AS A COMBUSTIBLE INSTEAD OF FLAMMABLE.  ALL MATERIAL IS BEING HELD IN CASE IT IS NEEDED AS EVIDENCE.  IF RELEASED, THE PRODUCT WILL BE USED BY THE AA AUTOMOTIVE MAINTENANCE DEPARTMENT IN THE GROUND EQUIPMENT.

IT IN TURN, HIT THE METAL FOOT OF A TOTE WHICH CAUSED THE LID OF ONE OF THE PAILS INSIDE OF THE CARTON TO FALL OFF ON IMPACT.  THE CONTENTS OF THIS PAIL SPILLED ALL OVER THE BOTTOM OF THE CARTON.

column168: ON 061098 AT APPROXIMATELY 11AM MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL SITE REMEDIATION, GEOFFREY REEDER RECEIVED A CALL OF A LEAKING TANK CAR AT SETTEGAST YARD.  THE CAR WAS REPORTED LEAKING FROM THE VENT AT THE TOP.  UPON ARRIVAL, REEDER REMOVED SEAL 349376 FROM THE VENT COVER.  THE RUPTURE DISC HAD FAILED.  REEDER INSTALLED A NEW 100# CDC DISC.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR NORMAL MOVEMENT.  CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED BY THE RISK MANAGEMENT COMMUNICATIONS CENTER.

AT 0145 HRS ON 6-10-98, CTS MGR WAS CONTACTED BY THE RISK MANAGEMENT COMMUNICATION DESK.  THEY ADVISED THAT CAR FOREMAN JOE DORNICK HAD REPORTED TANK CAR GATX 52824 LEAKING IN THE NORTH YARD AT DENVER, CO.   ONCE NOTIFIED MGR LERCH CONTACTED MR DORNICK WHO STATED THE FOLLOWING.  THE CAR WAS NOTED PRODUCT ON THE SIDES OF THE CAR AND AROUND THE MANWAY OPENING, AND THERE WAS NO LEAKAGE OF PRODUCT WHILE THE CAR WAS STATIONARY.   MGR LERCH ADVISED MR DORNICK TO ISOLATE CAR UNTIL NECESSARY REPAIRS COULD BE MADE.  INSPECTION BY MGR LERCH DETERMINED THAT THE RELEASE WAS CAUSE BY A FAILED SEAL ON THE MANWAY COVER DUE TO EXCESSIVE WEAR.  MGR LERCH APPLIED A GORTEX GASKET AROUND THE MANWAY OPENING AND SECURED THE MANWAY COVER WITHOUT FURTHER RELEASE OF PRODUCT.  AFTER SECURING CAR, MGR LERCH NEUTRALIZED THE SIDES OF THE CAR WITH A SODIUM BICARBONATE WASTER SOLUTION.  CAR ORIGINAL SEAL: MANWAY COVER, AGRIUM #8432,8432. REPLACED WITH UPRR EMG #002872.  NOTIFICATION: 1230HRS, 6-10-98, US AGRIUM, KERRY HADDOCK, MATERIAL MANAGER.

KT ANDERSON, SHOP FOREMAN, REPORTED TANKCAR PLMX 3947 WAS LEAKING IN THE YARD AT POCATELLO, ID.  THE SHOP WAS REPAIRING A WHEEL ON THE TANK CAR WHEN THEY SMELLED A STRONG AMMONIA ODOR.  THEY REMOVED THE TANKCAR AND SPOTTED IT ON RIP TRACK #0S1.  A LEAK WAS NOT ACTUALLY SEEN ON THE TANK CAR.  HARRY RODABOUGH, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY MANAGER, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  RMCC NOTIFIED CHEMTREC (JEFF) AND MICHELLE, AT CANUTEC.  INSPECTION REVEALED THE THERMOMETER WELL ASSEMBLY WAS LEAKING.  MGR. RODABOUGH REMOVED THE CAP VERY CAREFULLY AND TAPED THE BARREL OF THE WELL AND REPLACED THE CAP WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK BY ABOUT 50%, HOWEVER, THE LEAK CONTINUED AT THE THREADS ON THE MANWAY.  THE SHIPPER AND CONSIGNEE WERE BOTH NOTIFIED.  ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO HAVE MR. HUGH SHAWCROSS OF CANADIAN FERTILIZER VENT AND BURN THE REMAINING VAPORS IN THE CAR IN AN EFFORT TO REMOVE ALL PRESSURE FROM THE CAR.  THE THERMOMETER WELL WILL THEN BE REMOVED AND THE MANWAY PLUGGED.  THE CAR WILL THEN BE SHIPPED FOR REPAIRS.  CAPTAIN GLEN BLACKWELL OF THE POCATELLO FIRE DEPT WAS NOTIFIED AND INFORMED OF THE PENDING VENT AND BURN OPERATION.  HE ASKED THAT THEY BE NOTIFIED JUST PRIOR TO AND DIRECTLY AFTER THE OPERATION IS COMPLETED.

column168: RMCC, STEVE, NOTIFIED UPRR CTS MANGER ARLA ROQUET CARTER THAT THERE WAS VAPOR CLOUD RELEASE AT MONT BELVIEU.  THE LHX21 05, A LOCAL SWITCHER, SHOVED A CUT OF EIGHT CARS IN TRACK 717.  ONE OF THE CARS INVOLVED RELEASE A VAPOR CLOUD SEVERAL FOOTBALL FIELDS LONG.  THIS QUICKLY DISSIPATED.  THE CONDUCTOR CHECKED THE CARS INVOLVED AND FOUND NO ODOR, LEAKS, DAMAGE OR FURTHER SIGNS OF RELEASE.  IT WAS FELT THAT GATX 71605 WAS THE CAR INVOLVED.  THE CONSIGNEE, WARREN PETROLEUM, WAS NOTIFIED OF ITS POSSIBLE BEHAVIOR AND ACCEPTED THE CAR AND ADVISED THEY WOULD HANDLE.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Piping or Fittings
column168: MGR. CTS WILDER RECEIVED A CALL FROM THE  MTO AT CHICAGO HEIGHTS ADVISING THAT A TANK CAR WAS LEAKING BADLY AT THE CHICAGO HEIGHTS YARD.  UPON INSPECTION MGR WILDER FOUND TANK CAR RPBX 17139 LEAKING AT A RATE OF 10-15 GALLONS PER MINUTE.  MGR WILDER CONTACTED RMCC AND REQUESTED THAT THEY MAKE ALL NOTIFICATIONS.  MGR WILDER ALSO REQUESTED THAT MGR DON YORK RESPOND TO THE SCENE.  THE SHIPPER, RHODIA, RESPONDED WITH TWO THEIR GO TEAMS, ONE FROM CHICAGO HEIGHTS AND ONE FROM HAMMOND, IND.  THE REMAINING PRODUCT WAS TRANSLOADED INTO RPBX 17160.  THE TRANSLOADED PRODUCT WAS SHIPPED TO THE CHICAGO HEIGHTS PLANT FOR UNLOADING.  A THREE FOOT WIDE BY THREE FOOT DEEP DITCH WAS MADE FOR THE PRODUCT TO DRAIN INTO BETWEEN TRACKS 401 AND 402.  THE PRODUCT SPILLAGE WAS ABOUT 200 FEET LONG AND 50 FEET WIDE. ILLINOIS EPA WAS CALLED AND MR. WILDER REQUESTED THAT AN INSPECTOR FORM ILLINOIS EPA RESPOND TO THE SCENE.  IEPA RESPONDED AND AGREED TO THE CLEAN PLAN THAT WAS PRESENTED.  ON JUNE 10TH, BOTH TRACKS 401 AND 402 WHERE BACK IN SERVICE.  APPROXIMATELY 4200 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS TRANSPORTED TO CYLAND CHEM IN DETROIT, MI.  THE 250 YARDS OF SOIL WITH A PH LEVEL OF 3.5 WAS TAKEN TO CID LANDFILL IN CALLUMET CITY, IL.  FOURTEEN SOIL SAMPLES WERE TAKEN, SEVEN IN THE DITCH AND SEVEN FROM THE NORTH SIDE OF THE DITCH IN THE GRASS AREA. ALL THE TESTS WERE SENT TO FIRST ENVIRONMENTAL LABS IN NAPERVILLE, IL.  FURTHER TEST WILL BE TAKEN AT LATER DATES AFTER ANOTHER RAIN FALL PER ILLINOIS EPA REQUEST.  THE CAUSE OF THE RELEASE WAS BELIEVED TO BE AT THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE BOLTS.  THE BOLTS WERE LOOSE AND COULD NOT BE TIGHTENED.  RHODIA STATED TO MGR. WILDER THAT THEY HAD HAD PROBLEMS WITH THIS IN THE PAST, AND ADVISED THAT THE BOLTS NEEDED TO BE REPLACED WITH CHROME BOLTS SO THAT THE ACID WOULD NOT DETERIORATE THEM.  THE TANK CAR WAS RETURNED TO RHODIA OF GEISMAR, LA FOR FURTHER INSPECTION AND THEN FORWARDED TO THEIR SHOP FOR REPAIRS.

UPRR BOWL CAR FOREMAN REPORTED THAT TANK CAR UTLX 99361 LEAKING. THE CAR WAS A RESIDUE ANHYDROUS AMMONIA ENTRAINED ON THE MFWWT 04 IN TRACK 307.  UPRR CTS MANAGER ARLA ROQUET RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND FOUND THE SLIP TUBE GAUGING DEVICE WAS LEAKING AT THE PACKING GLAND NUT.  THIS WAS TIGHTENED AND THE VAPOR LEAK STOPPED.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT AT 0755 HRS.  RMCC WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT AT 0600 HRS.  RMCC WAS UPDATED AT 0804 HRS AND MADE NOTIFICATION TO CHEMTREC.

TANK CAR WAS LOCATED ON TRACK 501, NEXT TO THE ONE SPOT REPAIR SHOP, CHEYENNE YARDS.  INSPECTION REVEALED THAT VACUUM RELIEF VALVE WAS B/O AND LEAKING.  ALSO, BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS LEAKING. BLISS ADVISED THAT TANK CAR WILL COME BACK TO COASTAL CHEM TO BE UNLOADED AND PURGED AND WILL BE SHOPPED FOR REPAIRED.

MGR CTS WILDER WAS ADVISED BY MGR BRIAN URBAN THAT AN ARGON TANK CAR WAS VENTING AT CHICAGO HEIGHTS YARD.  INSPECTION BY MGR WILDER SHOWED THAT A CONTROL HANDLE WAS SLIGHTLY OPEN AND THIS WAS SECURED BY MGR. WILDER.  THE FRANGIBLE DISC HAD ALSO RUPTURED AND MGR WILDER CONTACTED THE SHIPPER, WHO DISPATCHED A SERVICE PERSON TO REPLACE THE RUPTURED DISC.  THE CAR WAS MOVED TO A INDUSTRIAL SIDING AT CHICAGO HEIGHTS FOR REPAIRS.  AFTER REPAIRS WERE COMPLETED, THE CAR WAS RETURNED TO SERVICE.

AB01798, SHPR: ALDRICH CHEMICAL, MKE8217507690 PAC. THIS IS A 5800.1 REPORT FORM ONLY. ON 6/13/98 AN ODOR WAS REPORTED AT ABX AIR, INC. 145 HUNTER DRIVE, Wilmington, OHIO 45177. PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIANS, ALAN HENDERSON AND CARL BOHL RESPONDED. UPON ARRIVAL THEY DISCOVERED A PLASTIC RECEPTACLE EMITTING AN ODOR. THE OUTER RECEPTACLE WAS MARKED, LABELED AND THE PROPER HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CERTIFICATION DID ACCOMPANY THIS SHIPMENT. THE LABELS ON THE OUTER PACKAGE WERE A CORROSIVE LABEL AND A CAO LABEL (CARGO AIRCRAFT ONLY). THE MARKINGS WERE THE PROPER SHIPPING NAME, UN# AND THE MANUFACTURE SEAL INFORMATION. AFTER FURTHER INSPECTION OF THE SHIPMENT THE TECHNICIANS FOUND THAT THE INNER SEAL HAD FAILED ON THE CLOSURE AND APPROXIMATELY 2 OUNCES OF 4.535 LITRE OF (CAPROIC ACID HAD LEAKED. THIS SHIPMENT WAS REPACKED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM DUE TO ODOR AND LEAKAGE AND FORWARDED TO THE DESTINATION.)

HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR TONY FRYE AND P/T SPILL TECHNICIAN TIM HINES RESPONDED. THEY DONNED AIR PURIFYING RESPIRATORS WITH HEPA CARTRIDGES. UPON ARRIVAL THEY FOUND A FIBRE BOARD BOX LOADED IN THE UNIT LOAD DEVICE AND INSPECTED. THEY OPENED THE BOX AND FOUND SIX 1 QUART METAL CANS WITH SCREW TYPE CLOSURES, WITH POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE THE CLOSURES. ONE OF TE INNER METAL CANS LEAKED THREE OUNCES DUE TO THE SHIPMENT BEING LOADED IMPROPERLY IN THE UNIT LOAD DEVICE. THEY CLEANED THE INNER CAN OF ANY LEAKAGE AND REPACKAGED THE SHIPMENT IN A RECOVERY DRUM TO FORWARD TO DESTINATION. THIS SHIPMENT WAS PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED AND CERTIFIED AS A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. FILE NAME AB 1398, SHIPPER: PRATT AND LAMBERT, AEB #ICT 8758513993 QTPD.

ON 6/4/98 AN ODOR WAS REPORTED IN BUILDING 207 OF OUR SORT FACILITY. HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR TONY FRYE AND P/T SPILL TECHNICIAN TIM HINES RESPONDED. THEY DONNED AIR PURIFYING RESPIRATORS WITH HEPA CARTRIDGES. UPON ARRIVAL THEY FOUND A FIVE GALLON METAL DRUM MARKED AND LABELED GAS OIL. UN1202, CLASS 3 AND CARGO AIRCRAFT ONLY. THEY INSPECTED THE DRUM AND FOUND THE CLOSURE, CLEANED THE DRUM OF ANY LEAKAGE AND FORWARDED THE DRUM ON TO ITS DESTINATION. THIS SHIPMENT WAS MARKED AND LABELED AND CERTIFIED AS A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. FILE NAME: AB 1198, SHIPPER: WILLIAMS LAB SERVICE, AWB# TUL 8782702891 IONA.

ON 6/11/98, A SPILL WITH AN ODOR WAS REPORTED IN BELLY TWO OF AIRCRAFT 819AZ PARKED ON C RAMP GATE C-23 OF OUR SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT ABX AIR INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE. WILMINGTON, OHIO 45177. P/T SPILL TECHNICIANS BRUCE SHILTZ AND ALAN HENDERSON RESPONDED. THEY DONNED AIR PURIFYING RESPIRATORS WITH HEPA CARTRIDGES. UPON ARRIVAL THEY FOUND A FIBRE BOARD BOX MARKED CONSUMER COMMODITY ORM-D WITH VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE. THEY TESTED THE LIQUID, PH READING OF 7. THEY OPENED THE BOX AND FOUND 4 INNER FIBRE BOARD BOXES EACH CONTAINING 12 AEROSOL CANS. ONE OF THE AEROSOL CANS IN ONE OF THE INNER BOXES HAD A SMALL HOLE IN THE BOTTOM SEAM CAUSING IT TO LEAK ITS ENTIRE CONTENTS OF 13 OUNCES. NONE OF THE OTHER AEROSOL CANS WERE COMPROMISED OF LEAKED. THIS SHIPMENT WAS REPACKAGED IN A RECOVERY DRUM AND MOVED TO DESTINATION. THERE WAS NO HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DOCUMENTATION ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT. THIS SHIPMENT WAS NOT PROPERLY PACKAGE OR MARKED FOR TRANSPORT BY AIR. CONTENTS OF THE AEROSOL CANS: "CRT" CLEANER. FILE NAME: AB01698, SHIPPER: NIGHT RIDER COPY SERVICE, AWB# IAH 4198462225 BGG.

ON 6/9/98, AN ODOR WAS REPORTED IN BUILDING 207 OF OUR SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT ABX AIR INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO 45177. P/T SPILL TECHNICIANS BRUCE SHILTZ AND ALAN HENDERSON RESPONDED. THEY DONNED AIR PURIFYING RESPIRATORS WITH HEPA CARTRIDGE. UPON ARRIVAL THEY FOUND A FIBRE BOARD BOX WITH NO VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE. THE BOX WAS MARKED, LABELED AND CERTIFIED AS RESIN SOLUTION, 30, UN 1866. THEY OPENED THE BOX AND FOUND TWO INNER BOXES, ONE OF WHICH WAS SHOWING VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE. THEY TESTED THE LIQUID, PH READING OF 7. THEY OPENED THE LEAKING BOX AND FOUND FIVE GLASS VIALS, TWO OF WHICH WERE BROKEN. THERE WAS NO ABSORBENT OR CUSHIONING MATERIAL USED TO PREVENT THE VIALS MOVEMENT INSIDE THE INNER BOX. THEY REPACKAGED THE SHIPMENT IN A RECOVERY DRUM AND FORWARDED THE SHIPMENT ON TO ITS DESTINATION. THIS SHIPMENT WAS PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED AND CERTIFIED AS A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. THE BROKEN GLASS VIALS CONTAINING THE RESIN SOLUTION WAS THE SOURCE OF THE ODOR. FILE NAME: AB01598, SHIPPER: HILTI, AWB#DFW 3788383620 VCT.

SEABAUGH ARRANGED TO HAVE TANK CAR ISOLATED IN TRACK #717 AND CALLED CONTRACTOR SPILL TECH TO NEUTRALIZE ACID SPILL LOCATED UNDER TANK CAR ON TRACK #4. ESTIMATED PRODUCT LOSS WAS FIVE GALLONS. column168: EARLY ON THE MORNING OF JUNE 23RD, 1:00 AM, THE POLICE RECEIVED A CALL OF A STRONG ANHYDROUS ODOR COMING FROM THE AREA OF THE DURAND FERTILIZER PLANT. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED ALONG WITH GALE WEISSINGER, THE CO-OPS EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSON FOR THE AREA. AFTER INVESTIGATION OF THE AREA IT WAS FOUND THAT A VALVE ON THE END OF A HOSE USED FOR FILLING A TENDER TRUCK HAD BEEN CRACKED OPEN. THE MAIN VALVE HAD BEEN CLOSED AND PADDLE LOCKED WHEN THE FERTILIZER PLANT CLOSED FOR BUSINESS THAT DAY. ALSO THE VALVES ON SEVERAL ANHYDROUS WAGON HOSES HAD BEEN OPENED BUT THE MAIN VALVES WERE UNTOUCHED. ALL OF THE GATES WERE SHUT AND LOCKED THAT EVENING ON THE CHAIN LINK FENCE AROUND THE AREA. IT APPEARS THAT THE ONLY EXPLANATION CAN BE VANDALISM. NO SUSPECTS HAVE BEEN IDENTIFIED AT THIS TIME.

column168: WEDNESDAY, JUNE 10, 1998: 2320: MTTX 2002 RELEASED AN UNKNOWN AMOUNT OF PRODUCT.  MILLINOCKET FIRE DEPARTMENT NOTIFIED AND AFTER INSPECTING THE CAR REPORTED THAT CAR DID NOT HAVE A LEAK AND HAD APPARENTLY VENTED DUE TO EXTREME TEMPERATURE CHANGES.  TWO EMPLOYEES WERE TRANSPORTED TO MILLINOCKET HOSPITAL FOR EXAMINATION.  NORTH YARD RE-OPENED ABOUT 0130. INJURIES WERE NOT SERIOUS. THURSDAY, JUNE 11, 1998: 0245: CAR AGAIN RELEASED AN UNKNOWN AMOUNT OF PRODUCT WHICH RESULTED IN A 3RD EMPLOYEE BEING TRANSPORTED TO MILLINOCKET HOSPITAL FOR EVALUATION.  MILLINOCKET FIRE DEPARTMENT AGAIN NOTIFIED ADN AFTER INSPECTION OF THE CAR FOR THE SECOND TIME ADVISED THE YARDMASTER THAT CAR WAS OK AND TO HAVE IT INSPECTED IN THE MORNING.  CAR WAS NOT TO BE MOVED UNTIL INSPECTED. TRACKS IN THE VICINITY OF SPUR G REMAINED CLOSED.  IONJURY NOT SERIOUS.  AFTER INSPECTION FO MTCX2002 DETERMINED THAT CAR DID NOT PRESENT AN IMMEDIATE DANGER TO EMPLOYES OR THE PUBLIC, THE TRACKS IN THE VICINITY OF SPUR G WERE REOPENED AT 11:15.  THE DECISION TO REOPEN THAT PORTION OF THE YARD WAS BASED ON THE INSPECTION BY MYSELF AND 2 DEP REPRESENTATIVES AND ONLY AFTER CLOSE CONSULTATION WITH IMC'S VICE PRESIDENT JON DIESCH AND THEIR SAFETY DEPARTMENT.  MR. DIESCH ADVISED THE CAR WOULD NOT BE A HAZARD TO OUR EMPLOYEES OR THE PUBLIC IN ITS CURRENT CONDITION AND FURTHER ADVISED THAT CAR MUST NOT BE MOVED UNTIL INSPECTED BY A SAFETY REPRESENTATIVE FROM THEIR COMPANY WHICH WOULD BE EN-ROUTE IMMEDIATELY.  THE CAR WAS LEFT ON SPUR G AND TRACK LOCKED OUT.  BOB WHITTER AND ONE OTHER REP FROM MAINE DEP WERE ON THE SCENE.  FRIDAY, JUNE 12, 1998: AT 09:30 IMC SAFETY OFFICER TIM BROGAN ARRIVED FROM CINCINNATI AND INSPECTED THE DOME AREA OF THECAR.  IT WAS DETERMINED AT THIS TIME THAT THERE WAS A LEAK IN THE AREA WHERE THE DOME BOLTS TO THE CAR SHELL.  MR. BROGAN TIGHTENED ALL ACCESSIBLE NUTS ON THE DOME AND WAS SUCESSFUL IN TIGHTENING ONE NUT BY ABOUT 1/2 TURN AND 2 FURTHER NUTS IN THE SUSPECTED AREA BY ABOUT 1/4 TURN EACH.  BLUE SIGNAL PROTECTION OF THECAR WAS REMOVED AND THE CAR WAS SHIFTED BACK AND FORTH BY A MILLINOCKET SWITCHER TO DISTURB THE PRODUCT.  NO FURTHER RELEASE WAS EVIDENT.  THECAR WAS RELEASED BACK TO THE YARDMASTER AT 1530.  CAR WEIGHED AT MILLINOCKET:GROSS 243750; TARE 91200; NET 152550.  AT ABOUT 2330 CAR INSPECTORS NOTICED A SMELL OF AMMONIA WHEN INSPECTING SOUTHBOUND TRAIN. UPON ARRIVAL OF JIM YOUNG AND MYSELF AT MILLINOCKET INSPECTION OF CAR DETERMINED CAR STILL HAD A LEAK. LES DRIVER, DAVID WEST, WAS DELIVERING A LOAD FROM HOECHST CELANESE-SPATANBURG, SC TO BRIDGEPORT NJ.  BRIDGEPORT COULD NO ACCEPT THIS LOAD UNTIL SATURDAY, JUNE 20, 1998.  THE BRIDGEPORT FACILITY REQUESTED OUR ASSISTANCE IN PICKING UP TWO LOADS FROM FMC- BALTIMORE WITH THEIR TANKERS WHILE OUR TANKER EASTERN TRANS-ROEBUCK) WAS BEING DETAINED FOR OFFLOADING. 3:00 PM  LES DRIVER DAVID WEST RECEIVED A SHIPMENT OF METHANOL HEPTANE FROM FMC CORP- BALTIMORE. DAVID WAS PULLING A TANKER FROM BRIDGEPORT, NJ#2201T) AND WAS SCHEDULED TO DELIVER THE LOAD TO THE BRIDGEPORT FACILITY. 5:00 P M  DAVID STOPPED AT THE PETRO TRUCK STOP OFF OF I-95 APPROXIMATELY 10 MILES FROM DELAWARE LINE FOR HIS REQUIRED 8 HOUR DOT BREAK.  THE ADDRESS IS BELL HILL ROAD, ELTON, MARYLAND, CEICLE COUNTY. 10:15 PM DAVID WAS AWAKENED BY ANOTHER DRIVER AT THE PETRO TRUCK STOP AND INFORMED THAT HIS TANKER WAS LEAKING .  DAVID PLACED A BUCKET UNDER THE TANK, ABSORBENT PADS AND OIL DRY IN AN EFFORT TO CONTAIN THE LEAKING MATERIAL. 10:25 PM FIRE DEPARTMENT TOOK OVER THE SITE. 10:30 PM DAVID NOTIFIED ME AND INFORMED ME TO THE LEAKING TANK. 10:45 PM I CALLED MIKE DAILEY AND REQUESTED ANOTHER TANKER BE DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE. MIKE SENT A VACUUM TANK FROM BRIDGEPORT FACILITY.  MIKE ALSO RESPONDED TO THE PETRO TRUCK STOP SPILLS.

WHILE LOADING ONE PIECE OF THE SHIPMENT IN HIS DELIVERY VAN, OUR COURIER GOT MATERIAL ON HIS HANDS AS THE BOTTOM OF THE BOX WAS WET.  AFTER WASHING HIS HANDS, HE ATTEMPTED TO LOAD THE PACKAGE AND GOT SOME MATERIAL ON HIS PANTS.  WHEN HE FELT A BURNING OR TINGLING ON HIS LEG, HE NOTIFIED THE SUPERVISOR.  THE SUPERVISOR SEGREGATED THE BOXES IN A SAFE AREA AND CALLED THE CONSIGNEE WHO IDENTIFIED THE MATERIAL AS PHOSPHORIC ACID , A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  THE SHIPMENT DID NOT HAVE HAZMAT LABELS AND THE CONTENTS WERE NOT IDENTIFIED AS HAZARDOUS ANYWAY.  THE CONSIGNEE PICKED UP THE SHIPMENT.  THE COURIER SUFFERED NO INJURIES AND REQUIRED NO MEDICAL TREATMENT.  THE PACKAGE WAS NOT OPENED OR THE CONTENTS INSPECTED FOR SAFETY REASONS.  THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED AND OUR INVESTIGATING (FAA AGENT BRAD CROWLEY 650-876-2995).

column168: CALL FROM ROGER POWELL AT 10:30 PM, HE WAS AT UPS TRUCK LEASING ON STATESVILLE AVE.  HE HAD JUST LEFT FROM THE FHF PLANT HAVING DIRTY DELEXES APPROXIMATELY 200.  HE PULLED INTO THE FUEL ISLAND AND ONE OF THE SHOP MECHANICS NOTICED SMOKE COMING FROM THE REAR OF THE TRUCK.  THEY OPENED THE TRAILER AND NOTICED A FIRE ON THE FLOOR. ROGER PULLED THE UNIT (485) AWAY FROM THE FUEL ISLAND AND HE AND THE MECHANIC USED A FIRE EXTINGUISHER TO PUT THE FIRE OUT.  BY THIS TIME THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND HAZMAT TEAM HAD ARRIVED AND THEY WERE INFORMED ON WHAT WAS ON THE TRAILER AND PROCEEDED TO CONTAIN THE SITUATION.   I,  RICK FOWLER, ARRIVED AT THE SCENE AT APPROXIMATELY 10:50 PM AND SPOKE WITH BATTALION CHIEF, BART MASSEY, AND HAZMAT COMMANDER NEWELL.  THEY PRETTY MUCH TOOK CARE OF THE SITUATION BY HOSING DOWN THE BURNED AREA AND ANY OTHER CONTAINERS THAT WERE INVOLVED.  THERE WERE 5 CONTAINERS THAT WERE BURNED OR MELTED AND ONE THAT WAS COMPLETELY MELTED WHICH WE PRESUME TO BE THE HYDROGEN PEROXIDE 35% CONTAINER. ENROUTE TO THE SCENE, I CONTACTED MIKE DEAL AND LEFT A VOICE MESSAGE WITH WILSON THOMPSON.  I HAD NO OTHER PHONE NUMBERS TO CALL.  BILLY COBB, ARVI KIVI WERE ADVISED ON 6/23/98 AT 6:30 AM.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT CONTINUED TO SPRAY H20 ON THE CONTAINERS TO COOL THEM DOWN.  RUN-OFF FROM THE SIGHT WAS CHECKED BY THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND WAS CONSIDERED SAFE.  THE RUN OF LEFT THE ASPHALT TO THE STORM DRAIN.  I DISPATCHED ANOTHER TRUCK TI COME PICK UP THE CONTAINERS INVOLVED AND THEY WERE PICKED UP AND BROUGHT BACK TO WORTH CHEMICAL WHERE THEY WASHED OUT AND THEN CUT UP FOR DISPOSAL.  THE TRAILER INVOLVED WAS CONSIDERED SAFE AND HE CONTINUED ON TO GREENSBORO.  SITE WAS SWEPT CLEAN AND WAS RELEASED.  THE INDIVIDUALS AT UPS TRUCK LEASING. THEY IN TURN CALLED HERITAGE ENVIRONMENTAL/CHRIS ALVIS WHICH IS THE COMPLIANCE MANAGER TO COME TO THE SCENE AND ADDRESS ANY ISSUE.  CHRIS CONTACTED THE CITY CONCERNING THE RELEASE TO THE STORM DRAIN WITH HE H20 THE FIRE DEPARTMENT USED AND THE MAJOR RAIN FALL THAT OCCURRED JUST AFTER THE FIRE DEPARTMENT LEFT EVERYTHING WAS NEUTRALIZED.  I LEFT THE SCENE AT APPROXIMATELY 2:15 AM.

WHITELEY, SPARKS, NV., WAS NOTIFIED BY RISK MANAGEMENT COMMUNICATION CENTER, DENVER, CO., THAT CAR FOREMAN PHIL AVERETT, ROPER YARD, SALT LAKE CITY, UT., HAD REPORTED TANK CAR GATX52489 WAS LEAKING RUST/AMBER COLORED MATERIAL FROM THE CENTER BOTTOM AREA OF TANK CAR. MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, HARRY RODABOUGH, WAS ADVISED OF THAT YARD PERSONNEL AT POCATELLO HAD HEARD A LOUD POP SOUND COMING FROM TANK CAR ARIX 1273.  THE YARDMASTER ADVISED THERE WAS NO APPARENT PRODUCT LOSS AND NO ODOR. THE CAR WAS ISOLATED PENDING AN INSPECTION BY MANAGER RODABOUGH .  TANK CAR WAS INSPECTED THE NEXT MORNING BY EMG MANAGER , ED BANKS AND HE REPORTED THAT THE CAR WAS LEAKING AND VENTING.   UPON ARRIVAL, MGR RODABOUGH INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND A DEFECTIVE 340 REGULATOR VALVE AND A LEAKING LIQUID VALVE.  MANAGER RODABOUGH ATTEMPTED TO RELEASED THE PRESSURE IN THE CAR BY OPENING THE VAPOR VALVE.  MANAGER ROADBOUGH CONTACTED THE SHIPPER, BOC GASES, WHO SUGGESTED THAT HE CONTACTED MR.  JOHN PALMER AT HURST TRUCKING, A SUBSIDIARY OF BOC AT POCATELLO,  AFTER CONSULTATION WITH MR. PALMER, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THAT CAR WAS OVERLOADED BY APPROXIMATELY 20,000 LBS AND THAT THE CAR WOULD REQUIRE TRANSLOADING.  TRANSLOADED OPERATIONS BEGAN AT 1330 HOURS AND WERE COMPLETED AT 1730 HOURS.  THREE AND A HALF LOADS OR APPROXIMATELY 135,000 POUNDS, WERE REMOVED FROM THE CAR.  CAR WAS TO BE RETURNED TO SHIPPER FOR REPAIRS.

column168: DEAN C COOPER, MGR OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY RON WESSEL, MECHANICAL FOREMAN, COLTON, CALIFORNIA, REPORTING A LEAKING TANK CAR.  FOREMAN WESSEL ADVISED THE ABOVE TANK CAR WAS IN THE LIGHT RIP TRACK #276, WAS NOTED LEAKING FROM THE TOP PORTION OF THE CAR WHILE THE TRACK WAS BEING SET DURING NORMAL SWITCHING OPERATIONS.   AS THE TANK CAR WAS ALL READY SET TO THE RIP TRACK, IT WAS LEFT IN PLACE WHERE IT COULD BE ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE COLTON YARD, INSPECTED THE TANK CAR, AND FOUND THE SOURCE THE LEAK TO BE FROM A BURST FRANGIBLE DISC IN THE SAFETY VENT.  THE SAFETY VENT, A STANDARD MIDLAND, LOCATED OUT SIDE THE WORK PLATFORM TOWARDS THE "A" END OF THE CAR, WAS DISASSEMBLED AND THE BURST DISC REPLACED WITH A LIKE TYPE BS&B 165 POUND DISC. THE SAFETY VENT WAS REASSEMBLED AND THE REMAINING VALVES AND FITTINGS INSPECTED, AND FOUND TO BE SECURE.  AS THE CAR WAS NOT OVERLOADED IT APPEARS THIS CAR WAS ROUGH HANDLED DURING SWITCHING OPERATIONS.  THERE WAS A SMALL PRODUCT TRAIL DOWN THE SIDE OF THE TANK CAR, WHICH WAS NEUTRALIZED.  THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE.  DUE TO THE NATURE OF THE COMMODITY, AND THE MINIMAL AMOUNT RELEASED, NOTIFICATIONS WERE ONLY MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND THE SHIPPER AS INFORMATION.

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: FLIGHT ARRIVED AT DFW WITH A BATTERY-ACID SPILL IN THR FORWARD CARGO COMPARIMENT. THE BATTERY WAS DECLARED BY THE PASSENGER AS NON- SPILLABLE. CONTRARY TO AA PROCEDURES, THE EMPLOYEE DID NOT VERIFTY THIS FACT. THE THE MOBILITY DEVICE WAS LOADED ON ITS SIDE AND BATTERY ACIDS LEAKED FROM THE FROM THE FITTINGS.THE ACIDS MADE CONTACT EITH A GROUND EMPLOYEE'S CLOTHING. AS A PRECAUTION, THE EMPLOYEE WAS TAKEN TO THE AA MEDICAL  FACILITY, CHECKED AND CLEARED TO RETURN TO DUTY. THE ACID  WAS CLEANED AND THE AIRCRAFT WAS RETURNED TO SERVICE. THIS REPORT IS BEING FILED IN COMPLIANCE WITH 49 CFR 171.16 AND IS NOT TO BE CONSTRUED AS THE COMPLETION OF THE AAL'S INVESTIGATION.
